  "1.05": [
    { text: "Peter Sachsa is based loosely on the real medium Rudi Schneider, investigated by psychical researchers in 1920s Vienna and London.", source: "Weisenburger, A Gravity's Rainbow Companion" },
    { text: "The séance scenes draw on the real history of the Society for Psychical Research, which operated from the 1880s and investigated mediums under laboratory conditions.", source: "Society for Psychical Research", url: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Society_for_Psychical_Research" },
  ],
  "1.10": [
    { text: "The 'Kenosha Kid' variations are a virtuoso exercise in syntactic ambiguity: the same seven words rearranged to produce dozens of different meanings, each one a different interrogation.", source: "Weisenburger, A Gravity's Rainbow Companion" },
    { text: "Sodium amytal (amobarbital) was used as a 'truth serum' in mid-century military and intelligence interrogations. Its use on Slothrop echoes real CIA programmes including MKULTRA.", source: "MKULTRA", url: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MKUltra" },
  ],
  "1.13": [
    { text: "Infant conditioning experiments were real: John B. Watson's 'Little Albert' study (1920) conditioned a baby to fear white rats. Pynchon's Jamf experiment transposes this into the novel's central mystery.", source: "Little Albert experiment", url: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Little_Albert_experiment" },
    { text: "The Poisson distribution debate between Pointsman and Mexico enacts the novel's philosophical core: determinism versus randomness, cause versus correlation.", source: "Poisson distribution", url: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poisson_distribution" },
  ],
  "1.16": [
    { text: "The Advent evensong scene is widely regarded as one of Pynchon's most lyrical passages. The hymn 'In Paradisium' and the toothpaste-tube-as-munition meditation compress wartime's sacred and profane into a single breath.", source: "Pynchon Wiki" },
  ],
  "1.19": [
    { text: "Walter Rathenau, the real German foreign minister assassinated in 1922, delivers a posthumous lecture on coal-tar chemistry and corporate cartelisation. Pynchon draws on Rathenau's actual writings about industrial mysticism.", source: "Walter Rathenau", url: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walther_Rathenau" },
    { text: "The Verein für Raumschiffahrt (Society for Space Travel) was the real amateur rocket club where Wernher von Braun and others began experimenting in the late 1920s. Pökler's Reinickendorf test echoes its early launches.", source: "Verein für Raumschiffahrt", url: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Verein_f%C3%BCr_Raumschiffahrt" },
  ],
  "2.04": [
    { text: "Brigadier Pudding's nocturnal visits to 'Domina Nocturna' (Katje in disguise) constitute the novel's most extreme scatological scene. Weisenburger reads it as a literalisation of the Great War's afterlife: the trenches have become an erotic ritual the old soldier cannot escape.", source: "Weisenburger, A Gravity's Rainbow Companion" },
  ],
  "3.02": [
    { text: "Slothrop's Rocketman costume is assembled from scraps in Nordhausen's black market. The superhero disguise parodies American pulp culture while granting Slothrop temporary legibility in the Zone's chaos.", source: "Pynchon Wiki" },
    { text: "See also: the dissolution field on the Dissolution page tracks how Slothrop's naming patterns multiply after he enters the Zone.", page: "/dissolution" },
  ],
  "3.04": [
    { text: "Enzian's backstory reaches to German South-West Africa and the Herero wars. His presence in the Zone as leader of the Schwarzkommando literalises the return of colonial violence to the European mainland.", source: "Herero and Nama genocide", url: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herero_and_Nama_genocide" },
  ],
  "3.19": [
    { text: "The Anubis, named for the Egyptian jackal-god of embalming, is a ship of the dead carrying Margherita Erdmann, her daughter Bianca, and a cargo of wartime atrocity. Bianca's death is among the novel's most contested scenes.", source: "Pynchon Wiki" },
    { text: "Margherita Erdmann's career in Weimar cinema connects her to the real UFA film studios, where Fritz Lang and others worked under conditions Pynchon fictionalises throughout.", source: "UFA GmbH", url: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UFA_GmbH" },
  ],
  "3.27": [
    { text: "Tchitcherine's posting to Central Asia to impose a New Turkic Alphabet on nomadic peoples parallels the real Soviet latinisation campaigns of the 1920s-30s, which forcibly replaced Arabic scripts across Central Asia.", source: "Latinisation in the Soviet Union", url: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latinisation_in_the_Soviet_Union" },
  ],
  "4.01": [
    { text: "The Counterforce's first organised action. Roger Mexico disrupts a formal dinner with obscenity, enacting Pynchon's vision of resistance as vulgarity, laughter, and refusal of decorum.", source: "Pynchon Wiki" },
    { text: "See also: the network atlas on the Network page shows how the Counterforce characters cluster in Part 4.", page: "/network" },
  ],
  "4.09": [
    { text: "Slothrop's 'scattering' is the novel's most radical formal gesture: the protagonist dissolves not through death but through loss of narrative coherence. He becomes a photograph, a song, a set of rumors.", source: "Weisenburger, A Gravity's Rainbow Companion" },
    { text: "See also: the dissolution field on the Dissolution page visualises this scattering as the progressive disappearance of Slothrop's name.", page: "/dissolution" },
  ],
  "2.05": [
    { text: "Shell's wartime role was real: Royal Dutch Shell's London headquarters was used as a V-2 guidance signal relay, and Duncan Sandys coordinated rocket intelligence from Shell Mex House on the Strand.", source: "Weisenburger, A Gravity's Rainbow Companion" },
    { text: "IG Farben's cross-licensing agreements with Standard Oil, ICI, and Shell created the cartel network Pynchon fictionalises. The real agreements survived into the postwar period.", source: "IG Farben", url: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IG_Farben" },
  ],
  "2.06": [
    { text: "The Zoot Suit Riots (June 1943) saw US servicemen attack Mexican-American youths in Los Angeles. Slothrop's borrowed zoot suit carries this history of racial violence as literal fabric.", source: "Zoot Suit Riots", url: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zoot_Suit_Riots" },
  ],
  "3.03": [
    { text: "The rocket mandala KEZVH integrates Herero cosmology with the V-2's geometry: the five directions (up, down, north, south, and centre) mapped onto the rocket's own coordinates of thrust, guidance, and descent.", source: "Pynchon Wiki" },
    { text: "The Empty Ones' doctrine of tribal self-extinction inverts the logic of the Vernichtungsbefehl. Survival itself becomes a theological question rather than a biological one.", source: "Georgetown Digital Repository", url: "https://repository.digital.georgetown.edu/handle/10822/553016" },
  ],
  "3.05": [
    { text: "The Soviet latinisation campaigns (1920s-30s) forcibly replaced Arabic scripts across Central Asia with Latin and later Cyrillic alphabets, erasing literary traditions in the name of modernisation.", source: "Latinisation in the Soviet Union", url: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latinisation_in_the_Soviet_Union" },
    { text: "The 'Kirghiz Light' may allude to the Tunguska event (1908) or to atmospheric phenomena observed in Central Asian deserts. Pynchon leaves its nature undetermined.", source: "Pynchon Wiki" },
  ],
  "3.14": [
    { text: "The Anubis is named for the Egyptian god of embalming and the dead. As a ship-of-the-dead motif it draws on both the Flying Dutchman and the Ship of Fools tradition.", source: "Pynchon Wiki" },
  ],
  "3.15": [
    { text: "The Bianca episode is among the novel's most contested passages. Critical readings range from literal paedophilia to allegorical readings of American innocence consumed by European decadence.", source: "Weisenburger, A Gravity's Rainbow Companion" },
  ],
  "3.25": [
    { text: "The KEZVH mandala combines Herero sacred geometry with rocket engineering: five points encoding the relationship between ancestors, fire, birth, and the four cardinal directions.", source: "Pynchon Wiki" },
    { text: "This scene is the only moment in the novel where Slothrop is genuinely welcomed into a community. He will never experience this again.", source: "Weisenburger, A Gravity's Rainbow Companion" },
  ],
  "3.28": [
    { text: "Fritz Lang's Dr. Mabuse films (1922, 1933, 1960) depicted a criminal mastermind controlling society through hypnosis and technology. Pynchon uses the films as templates for charismatic industrial power.", source: "Dr. Mabuse", url: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dr._Mabuse" },
  ],
  "3.30": [
    { text: "Operation Backfire (1945) was the real British programme to test-fire captured V-2 rockets at Cuxhaven with the help of German technicians, before the knowledge was transferred to the US and USSR.", source: "Operation Backfire", url: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operation_Backfire_(Post_World_War_II)" },
  ],
  "4.03": [
    { text: "The Phoebus cartel (1924-39) was a real conspiracy among lightbulb manufacturers (Osram, Philips, GE) to limit bulb lifespan to 1,000 hours, the first documented case of planned obsolescence.", source: "Phoebus cartel", url: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phoebus_cartel" },
    { text: "Byron the Bulb is widely read as an allegory for consciousness trapped within industrial systems: immortal awareness coupled with total impotence. Some critics call it the novel's secret centre.", source: "Weisenburger, A Gravity's Rainbow Companion" },
  ],
  "4.04": [
    { text: "The Katje-Enzian scene is the only moment two of Blicero's former captives meet and speak openly about what was done to them. It functions as mutual witness testimony.", source: "Pynchon Wiki" },
  ],
  "4.08": [
    { text: "The Disgusting English Candy Drill (4.08) echoes the English sweets ordeal in 1.15. Both weaponise oral disgust, but here the Counterforce turns it outward against institutional power.", source: "Weisenburger, A Gravity's Rainbow Companion" },
  ],
  "4.11": [
    { text: "Tchitcherine and Enzian pass each other without recognition, the novel's colonial fraternity dissolved by magic rather than resolved by confrontation. The brothers will never meet again.", source: "Pynchon Wiki" },
    { text: "Geli Tripping's love-spell works through sympathetic magic (toenail clippings, spoken words). The novel grants occult causality equal standing with Pavlovian and corporate causality.", source: "Weisenburger, A Gravity's Rainbow Companion" },
  ],
};

type Ep = {
  id: string; part: number; isHinge: boolean;
  synopsis: string;
  quotes: { label: string; quote: string; note: string }[];
  hingeCommentary: string; hingeAtmosphere: string;
  meta: MetaRow | undefined;
  annotations: Annotation[];
};

const episodes: Ep[] = unifiedData.map((u: any) => {
  return {
    id: u.episode_id,
    part: u.part,
    isHinge: HINGES.has(u.episode_id),
    synopsis: colourStrandRefs(synopsesMap.get(u.episode_id) || ''),
    quotes: quotesMap.get(u.episode_id) || [],
    hingeCommentary: HINGE_COMMENTARIES[u.episode_id] || '',
    hingeAtmosphere: HINGE_ATMOSPHERE[u.episode_id] || '',
    meta: metaMap.get(u.episode_id),
    annotations: ANNOTATIONS[u.episode_id] || [],
  };
});

const p1 = episodes.filter((e: Ep) => e.part === 1);
const p2 = episodes.filter((e: Ep) => e.part === 2);
const p3a = episodes.filter((e: Ep) => e.part === 3 && parseInt(e.id.split('.')[1]) <= 10);
const p3b = episodes.filter((e: Ep) => e.part === 3 && parseInt(e.id.split('.')[1]) > 10);
const p4 = episodes.filter((e: Ep) => e.part === 4);
---

<Layout title="The Braid" description="Eight plotlines braiding through seventy-three episodes.">
  <Nav slot="nav" />

  <main class="braid">
    <section class="braid-intro">
      <h1 class="braid-hero-title reveal">
        <span class="braid-hero-prefix"><em>Gravity&rsquo;s Rainbow</em> is a</span>
        <span class="braid-hero-word">braid</span>
      </h1>
      <p class="intro-text reveal">
        Eight plotlines weave through seventy-three episodes across four parts,
        thickening where they govern structure, thinning where they yield:
        pursuit, sacrifice, counter-text, complicity, control, love,
        counter-line, and image. What follows is the novel read as that braid:
        each episode placed in sequence, its active strands named, its
        inner workings made visible. Scroll as one would read.
      </p>
    </section>

    <div class="braid-scroll">
      <div class="braid-header" id="braid-header">
        <div class="braid-viz-wrap">
          <svg
            class="braid-viz"
            viewBox={`0 0 ${TOTAL_W} ${TOTAL_H}`}
            preserveAspectRatio="xMidYMid meet"
            role="img"
            aria-label="Interactive braid: eight plotlines across seventy-three episodes"
          >
            {/* Strand labels (left edge) */}
            {PLOTLINE_KEYS.map((pk, ri) => (
              <text
                class="braid-label"
                x={LABEL_W - 3}
                y={PAD_TOP + ri * ROW_H + ROW_H / 2 + 1}
                text-anchor="end"
                data-strand={pk}
                style={`fill: var(${STRAND_CSS_VAR[pk]}); cursor: pointer`}
              >
                {STRAND_SHORT[pk]}
              </text>
            ))}

            {/* Hinge column highlights */}
            {braidCols.filter(c => c.isHinge).map(c => (
              <rect
                x={c.x}
                y={0}
                width={COL_W}
                height={TOTAL_H}
                fill="var(--color-accent)"
                opacity="0.06"
                rx="1"
              />
            ))}

            {/* Part boundary lines */}
            {partBoundaries.map(bx => (
              <line
                x1={bx} y1={0} x2={bx} y2={TOTAL_H}
                stroke="var(--color-text-dim)"
                stroke-width="0.8"
                stroke-dasharray="2,2"
                opacity="0.5"
              />
            ))}

            {/* Intensity cells */}
            {braidCells.map(cell => (
              <rect
                x={cell.x}
                y={cell.y}
                width={cell.w}
                height={cell.h}
                rx="1.5"
                style={`fill: var(${cell.cssVar})`}
                opacity={cell.opacity}
              />
            ))}

            {/* Clickable episode columns (transparent hit areas) */}
            {braidCols.map(c => (
              <rect
                class="braid-col-hit"
                x={c.x}
                y={0}
                width={COL_W}
                height={TOTAL_H}
                fill="transparent"
                data-ep={c.epId}
                style="cursor:pointer"
              />
            ))}

            {/* Scroll cursor (moves via JS) */}
            <rect
              class="braid-cursor"
              id="braid-cursor"
              x={LABEL_W}
              y={0}
              width={COL_W}
              height={TOTAL_H}
              fill="var(--color-accent)"
              opacity="0"
              rx="1"
            />
          </svg>
        </div>
        <div class="scroll-track">
          <span class="scroll-part-label" id="scroll-part-label">Part 1</span>
          <div class="scroll-bar">
            <div class="scroll-ticks">
              <span class="tick" style="left: 28.77%"></span>
              <span class="tick" style="left: 39.73%"></span>
              <span class="tick" style="left: 83.56%"></span>
            </div>
            <div class="scroll-fill" id="scroll-fill"></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="reading-col">
        {p1.map((ep: Ep) => (
          <article class:list={['ep-panel', { hinge: ep.isHinge }]} id={`ep-${ep.id}`} data-part="1">
            <header class="ep-head">
              <span class="ep-id">{ep.id}</span>
              <span class="ep-part">Part {ep.part}</span>
            </header>
            {ep.meta && (
              <p class="ep-setting">{ep.meta.time}, {ep.meta.location} · {ep.meta.focalisation}</p>
            )}
            <p class="ep-synopsis" set:html={ep.synopsis} />
            {ep.hingeCommentary && (
              <div class="hinge-commentary">
                <p>{ep.hingeCommentary}</p>
              </div>
            )}
            {ep.quotes.length > 0 && (
              <div class="quote-block">
                {ep.quotes.map((q: { label: string; quote: string; note: string }) => (
                  <blockquote class="pull-quote">
                    {q.label && <span class="quote-anchor-label">{q.label}</span>}
                    <p>&lsquo;{q.quote}&rsquo;</p>
                  </blockquote>
                ))}
              </div>
            )}
            {ep.hingeAtmosphere && (
              <p class="hinge-atmosphere">{ep.hingeAtmosphere}</p>
            )}
            {ep.annotations.length > 0 && (
              <aside class="sidenotes">
                {ep.annotations.map((a: Annotation) => (
                  <div class="sidenote">
                    <p class="sidenote-text">{a.text}</p>
                    {a.url ? (
                      <a class="sidenote-source" href={a.url} target="_blank" rel="noopener">{a.source}</a>
                    ) : a.page ? (
                      <a class="sidenote-source sidenote-internal" href={`${base}${a.page}`}>{a.source}</a>
                    ) : (
                      <span class="sidenote-source">{a.source}</span>
                    )}
                  </div>
                ))}
              </aside>
            )}
          </article>
        ))}

        <div class="part-transition reveal">
          <p>
            Part 1 ends on Christmas Eve, with the London Blitz still falling.
            Slothrop&rsquo;s map, Pointsman&rsquo;s rats, Blicero&rsquo;s
            fairy tale, Pökler&rsquo;s chemistry, Roger and Jessica&rsquo;s
            love, all have been set in motion, but the Schwarzkommando and
            Tchitcherine have not yet appeared. Part 2 compresses the novel into
            eight episodes and moves it south: Slothrop at the Casino Hermann
            Goering, the octopus rescue, Katje&rsquo;s departure, the Pudding
            ritual, the Imipolex trail through Zurich, and finally
            Pointsman&rsquo;s collapse on a crowded beach. By its end, the
            institutional world that held Part 1 together has broken apart.
          </p>
        </div>

        {p2.map((ep: Ep) => (
          <article class:list={['ep-panel', { hinge: ep.isHinge }]} id={`ep-${ep.id}`} data-part="2">
            <header class="ep-head">
              <span class="ep-id">{ep.id}</span>
              <span class="ep-part">Part {ep.part}</span>
            </header>
            {ep.meta && (
              <p class="ep-setting">{ep.meta.time}, {ep.meta.location} · {ep.meta.focalisation}</p>
            )}
            <p class="ep-synopsis" set:html={ep.synopsis} />
            {ep.hingeCommentary && (
              <div class="hinge-commentary">
                <p>{ep.hingeCommentary}</p>
              </div>
            )}
            {ep.quotes.length > 0 && (
              <div class="quote-block">
                {ep.quotes.map((q: { label: string; quote: string; note: string }) => (
                  <blockquote class="pull-quote">
                    {q.label && <span class="quote-anchor-label">{q.label}</span>}
                    <p>&lsquo;{q.quote}&rsquo;</p>
                  </blockquote>
                ))}
              </div>
            )}
            {ep.hingeAtmosphere && (
              <p class="hinge-atmosphere">{ep.hingeAtmosphere}</p>
            )}
            {ep.annotations.length > 0 && (
              <aside class="sidenotes">
                {ep.annotations.map((a: Annotation) => (
                  <div class="sidenote">
                    <p class="sidenote-text">{a.text}</p>
                    {a.url ? (
                      <a class="sidenote-source" href={a.url} target="_blank" rel="noopener">{a.source}</a>
                    ) : a.page ? (
                      <a class="sidenote-source sidenote-internal" href={`${base}${a.page}`}>{a.source}</a>
                    ) : (
                      <span class="sidenote-source">{a.source}</span>
                    )}
                  </div>
                ))}
              </aside>
            )}
          </article>
        ))}

        <div class="part-transition reveal">
          <p>
            Part 3 is the explosion. Thirty-two episodes, nearly half the
            novel, scatter across postwar Europe&rsquo;s rubble. Slothrop
            adopts the Rocketman costume, boards the Anubis, plays Plechazunga
            the Pig-Hero, and slowly dissolves into the Zone&rsquo;s geography.
            Enzian&rsquo;s Schwarzkommando and Tchitcherine&rsquo;s Soviet
            intelligence service appear for the first time. Pökler arrives at
            Dora. Greta Erdmann tells her story aboard a ship of the dead.
            The Counterforce begins to organise. Nothing holds the centre
            because there is no centre to hold.
          </p>
        </div>

        <figure class="fig-plate reveal">
          <ModalHeatmap />
          <figcaption class="plate-caption">
            Beneath the characters and their stories, the novel sustains ten
            distinct emotional and intellectual currents, science, comedy,
            film, theology, paranoia, sexuality, and more, that rise and
            fall independently of who is on stage. The rocket&rsquo;s physics
            dominate 1.14 and 4.05; the corporate-military world saturates
            Parts 2 and 3 without releasing. A book whose emotional weather
            cannot be predicted from its plot.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        {p3a.map((ep: Ep) => (
          <article class:list={['ep-panel', { hinge: ep.isHinge }]} id={`ep-${ep.id}`} data-part="3">
            <header class="ep-head">
              <span class="ep-id">{ep.id}</span>
              <span class="ep-part">Part {ep.part}</span>
            </header>
            {ep.meta && (
              <p class="ep-setting">{ep.meta.time}, {ep.meta.location} · {ep.meta.focalisation}</p>
            )}
            <p class="ep-synopsis" set:html={ep.synopsis} />
            {ep.hingeCommentary && (
              <div class="hinge-commentary">
                <p>{ep.hingeCommentary}</p>
              </div>
            )}
            {ep.quotes.length > 0 && (
              <div class="quote-block">
